The Limit of Panic
Copenhagen — We often hear that the world we know will meet its end, usually described as ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Roman Club published the seminal work "The Limits to Growth" more than forty years ago, its basic idea has been with us ever since.
But time is not forgiving.
"The Limits to Growth" of 1972 warned humanity that a catastrophic collapse was imminent.
But since then, we have seen financial panics, yet no real shortages or production collapses.
On the contrary, the resources created by human ingenuity more than adequately satisfy human consumption.
But the basic idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds: we continue a trend of being preoccupied with misleading solutions to minor issues, while neglecting major problems and sensible solutions.
In the early 1970s, technological optimism faded, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" ignited public panic over pollution and also sparked the modern environmental movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title "The Population Bomb" said it all.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were filled with pessimism.
The intent of "The Limits to Growth" was to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people want to consume too much.
Even though our ingenuity has given us some time, in the end we will destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope is to halt economic growth itself, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a significantly poorer level than the present.
This view still resonates today, despite being profoundly mistaken.
For example, the authors of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that by 2013, the world would have exhausted aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc.
However, even though commodity prices have recently rebounded, overall they have fallen to one-third of the level from 150 years ago.
Technological innovation replaced mercury in batteries, dental materials, and thermometers, and by 2000, mercury consumption had decreased by 98%, and its price had fallen by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, the supply of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc has exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new refining technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally predicted to be exhausted by 1990 and 1992 respectively; today, reserves of both are higher than the 1970 levels, despite a significant increase in our consumption.
In the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves of the United States, cutting prices in half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14-fold this century, with developing countries seeing a 24-fold increase.
The Limits to Growth was wrong because the authors overlooked the greatest resource: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has been slowing since the 1960s.
Food supply has not collapsed (1.5 billion hectares of arable land are currently in use, with an additional 2.7 billion hectares in reserve).
Malnutrition rates have been reduced by more than half, falling from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has not stumped us either.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past in which we had no air pollution from particulates and were all happy farmers, while in the future, heating chimneys would make it impossible for us to breathe. Reality is exactly the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, yet nearly 3 million people — one in every 500 — died each year from air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Now, this figure has dropped to one death in every 2000 people.
Although the number of deaths caused by pollution is still higher than that from malaria, its mortality rate is decreasing rather than increasing.
Nevertheless, the ideas cultivated by *The Limits to Growth* continue to influence the thinking of the public and elites.
Take recycling, for example—it is usually just a feel-good gesture that costs the environment a great deal while yielding little benefit.
For example, paper usually comes from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The processes and government subsidies related to paper recycling result in low-quality paper, protecting resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, fears of overpopulation have led to self-defeating policies, such as China's one-child policy and India's forced sterilization.
In addition, although pesticides and other pollutants were thought to kill half the human population, effective pesticide regulation has limited annual deaths in the United States to just 20 cases, while pesticide use has created a cheaper and more abundant food supply.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture— a movement fueled by pesticide panic— would impose an additional $100 billion annual cost on the United States.
Agricultural efficiency would decrease by 16%, and to maintain current output, an additional 65 million hectares of farmland—roughly half the size of modern-day California—would have to be cultivated.
Rising prices will lead to a decline in fruit and vegetable consumption, causing severe negative health impacts, including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer-related deaths each year.
Getting lost in bleak scenarios prevents us from focusing on the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the greatest killers, and easily curable diseases still cause 15 million deaths each year—equivalent to a quarter of the total death toll.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people are lifted out of poverty, most can afford the burden of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past three decades, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world in reducing the number of people living in poverty by nearly a billion.
This has led to widespread improvements in health, life expectancy, and quality of life.
The forty-year history since the release of *The Limits to Growth* shows that we need more, not less, growth.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring over $10 trillion in annual benefits by the end of this century, a benefit far exceeding the timid "feel-good" policies driven by fear-mongering.
But this requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our boundless potential to create a brighter future.
